5":"1285","About 1310":"oko 1310.","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England"},"cs":{"abot 1285–":"1285–Zesnulá","1285–Male":"1285–Zesnulý","1310–Male":"1310–Zesnulý","1285–Female":"1285–Zesnulá","1315":"1315","1310":"1310","abot 1285":"1285","1285":"1285","About 1310":"okolo 1310","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"Anglie"},"da":{"abot 1285–":"1285–Afdød","1285–Male":"1285–Afdød","1310–Male":"1310–Afdød","1285–Female":"1285–Afdød","1315":"1315","1310":"1310","abot 1285":"1285","1285":"1285","About 1310":"omkring 1310","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England"},"nl":{"abot 1285–":"1285–Overleden","1285–Male":"1285–Overleden","1310–Male":"1310–Overleden","1285–Female":"1285–Overleden","1315":"1315","1310":"1310","abot 1285":"1285","1285":"1285","About 1310":"circa 1310","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England"},"en":{"abot 1285–":"1285–Deceased","1285–Male":"1285–Deceased","1310–Male":"1310–Deceased","1285–Female":"1285–Deceased","1315":"1315","1310":"1310","abot 1285":"1285","1285":"1285","About 1310":"about 1310","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Clare","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (Clare, Wicklow, and Wexford): habitational name from Clare in Suffolk (an eastern county of England), the center of a major Norman baronial estate since the Norman Conquest. The English placename probably originated as a Celtic river name meaning ‘bright, gentle, or warm’. The surname is not from the Irish county name <i>Clare</i>, which is either from the surname or from a place called with Gaelic <i>clár</i> ‘plank bridge’. Another Norman surname in the southeast of Ireland was <i>de Clere</i>, from Clères in Seine-Maritime (France), named from the local river.","English and French: from the Middle English, Old French female personal name <i>Cla(i)re</i> (from Latin <i>Clara</i>, from <i>clarus</i> ‘clear, bright, famous’) which achieved some popularity, greater elsewhere in Europe than in England, through the fame of Saint Clare of Assisi (see   Chiara  ). The English surname seems to have been interchangeable with   Clear   1.","English: occupational name from an agent derivative of Middle English <i>cley</i> ‘clay’. The work of medieval clayers involved plastering a framework of interwoven twigs with mud to produce wattle-and-daub work."],"variants":[{"name":"Claire","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Clare  .","Variant of   Clair  , an altered form of German   Klare  .","French: variant of   Clair  ."]},{"name":"Chiara","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Marco, Amedeo, Angelo, Gino, Rocco.","Italian: from the female personal name <i>Chiara</i> or <i>Clara</i>, a name popularized in the medieval period by the cult of Saint Clare of Assisi (<i>c.</i> 1193–1253); she was an associate of Saint Francis of Assisi and founded the order of nuns known as the Poor Clares. See also   Chiaro  ."]},{"name":"Claar","meanings":["German: variant of <b>Klaar</b> (and, in North America, an altered form of this), a nickname from Middle High German, Middle Low German <i>klar</i> ‘pure, pretty, sensible’, or a habitational name from a minor place so named near Braunschweig.","Possibly also an Americanized form of Dutch <b>Klaar</b>: from a vernacular form of the female personal name <i>Clara</i> (see   Clare   2)."]},{"name":"Clarkin","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Cheshire): from a pet form of the personal name <i>Clare</i> (compare   Clare   and   Clear  ), which is both a masculine and a female personal name in Middle English.","Irish (Monaghan): variant of   Clerkin  ."]},{"name":"Clear","meanings":["English (southeastern England, of Norman origin): from <i>Clere</i>, the French popular form of the personal name   Clare   2, and possibly interchangeable with it or confused with it.","English (southeastern): probably a habitational name from clere, a component of several placenames in north Hampshire (Highclere, Burghclere, Kingsclere). This is probably from a Celtic stream name meaning ‘bright’ (cognate with Latin <i>clarus</i> ‘clear, bright’).","Americanized form (translation into English) of German   Klar   1."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."],"variants":[{"name":"Anni","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":5,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705191,"age":30,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":43,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Anne Clare was born in 1285, in England. She had at least 1 son with Sir John le Gross."},"et":{"abot 1285–":"1285–Surnud","1285–Male":"1285–Surnud","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1285–Female":"1285–Surnud","1315":"1315","1310":"1310","abot 1285":"1285","1285":"1285","About 1310":"umbes 1310","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England"},"fi":{"abot 1285–":"1285–Kuollut","1285–Male":"1285–Kuollut","1310–Male":"1310–Kuollut","1285–Female":"1285–K